'''Dr. Gustav Milne''' is a British Archaeologist, writer and TV contributor who is the current project lead for [[Coastal and Intertidal Zone Archaeological Network]] and Honorary Senior Lecturer at the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology]].

==History==
Gustav Milne studied archaeology at [[University of Oxford]] and completed his [[Master of Philosophy|MPhi]] at the [[University of London]], where he wrote a thesis on ancient harbor installations.<ref name=thamesdis>{{cite web|url=http://www.thamesdiscovery.org/contact/gustav-milne|title=Gustav Milne - Project Director - Thames Discovery Project|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> Gustav started his career as a volunteer for the [[Museum of London|Guildhall Museum]] at the site of [[Custom House, City of London|Custom House]] in the City of London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/community-lecture-45-years-of-foreshore-archaeology-with-gustav-milne-tickets-45230374267#|title=Community Lecture: 45 Years of Foreshore Archaeology with Gustav Milne by Thames Discovery Programme - Event Brite|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> Between 1973 and 1991 Gustav worked for the [[Museum of London]] as a professional rescue archaeologist, working on various archaeological digs including [[Pudding Lane]] and the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[London Bridge]].<ref name=Amaz>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Gustav-Milne/e/B001HPGY0C|title=Gustav Milne - Amazon|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> During this time he wrote many reports on his findings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/library/browse/issue.xhtml?recordId=1087975&recordType=MonographSeries|title=Milne, G. and Milne, C., (1982). Medieval waterfront development at Trig Lane, London: an account of the excavations at Trig Lane, London, 1974-6 and related research. p.1982 |isbn=0 903290 24 3|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> 

In 1991 Gustav joined [[UCL Institute of Archaeology]] as a Senior Lecturer (in London Archaeology and Maritime Archaeology).<ref name=thamesdis></ref> In 1992 Gustav became the secretary of the newly formed London Archaeological Research facility.<ref name=AI>{{cite web|url=https://www.ai-journal.com/articles/10.5334/ai.0205/galley/239/download/|title=A capital concern: the Institute and London's archaeology - Archaeology International|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> In 1993 he founded the Thames Archaeology Survey,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mola.org.uk/people/gustav-milne|title=Gustav Milne - MOLA|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> a project to compile an inventory of archaeological and palaeo-environmental sites exposed between [[Teddington]] and [[Dartford]],<ref name=AI></ref> before going onto form the [[Thames Discovery Programme]] in 2008. In 2013, Gustav was nominated as one of Current Archaeology's "Archaeologists of the Year" and the Thames Discovery Programme won the Archaeology Training Forum's Training Award, which was presented at the IfA Conference in Birmingham. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thamesdiscovery.org/frog-blog/atf-award-winners |title=ATF Award |publisher=thamesdiscovery.org.uk |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

In 2015 he helped create the [[Coastal and Intertidal Zone Archaeological Network]] (CITiZAN) which he currently holds the position of Project Leader, and the founder and co-ordinator for [[University College London|UCL]] 'Evolutionary Determinants of Health' programme.<ref name=Amaz></ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1492663/1/302-2032-1-PB.pdf|title=RESEARCH ARTICLE - The Evolutionary Determinants of Health Programme Urban Living in the 21st Century from a Human Evolutionary Perspective - Gustav Milne - archaeology international|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theplanner.co.uk/author/gustav-milne|title=Gustav Milne - The Planner|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> Gustav has also set up the [[Museum of London]]'s Centre for Human Bioarchaeology with a grant from the [[Wellcome Trust]].<ref name=UCL>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/staff/staff-news/November/29112016-spotlight-on-gustav-milne|title=Spotlight on Gustav Milne - UCL|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref>

==Television Work==
Gustav has appeared as an archaeology expert on several Television programme since the 1990s, with many appearances on [[Time Team]] amongst those.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1596304/|title=Gustav Milne - IMDb|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> He has also appeared as a contributor to ''Digging for Britain - The Tudors'' and TV documentaries ''The Bridges That Built London'' and ''Fire, Plague, War and Treason''. Through his project leadership at CITiZAN, in 2016 he assisted Tern TV in setting up the archaeology program [[Britain at Low Tide]].<ref name=UCL></ref> In 2018 he became a regular contributor for the [[Channel 4]] program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mola.org.uk/blog/britain-low-tide-returns-channel-4-explore-history-our-island-nation|title=Britain at Low Tide returns to Channel 4 to explore the history of our island nation - mola.org.uk|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>

