==Reception== Steve Raiteri from [[Library Journal]] commends ''Mechademia'' as a "great first effort [...] bridg[ing] the gap between academics and fans."<ref name=Raiteri>{{cite web|url=http://www.libraryjournal.com/article/CA6403916.html |title=Graphic Novels: Religion and Comics |last=Raiteri |first=Steve |date=2007-01-15 |publisher=[[Library Journal]] |accessdate=2009-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625221944/http://www.libraryjournal.com/article/CA6403916.html |archivedate=2009-06-25 |df= }} </ref> Christophe Thouny, writing for ''Animation'' also thought the writing and tone was accessible by both academics and fans.<ref name=Thouny>{{cite journal |last=Thouny |first=Christophe |year=2008 |title=Untitled Review |journal=Animation |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=212–217 |doi=10.1177/17468477080030020703 }}</ref> Ed Sizemore from Comics Worth Reading criticizes the journal for its review and commentary section because they "read like summaries of the works (films and books) discussed with no actual critique of the work". However, Sizemore commends the journal's academic essay section.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicsworthreading.com/2007/06/25/mechademia-1/ |title=Mechademia 1 |last=Sizemore |first=Ed |date=June 25, 2007 |publisher=Comics Worth Reading |accessdate=2009-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125025446/http://comicsworthreading.com/2007/06/25/mechademia-1/ |archivedate=November 25, 2009 |df= }}</ref>
By contrast, Raiteri in [[Library Journal]] states that fans will find the Review and Commentary section "the most accessible" section of the journal.<ref name=Raiteri /> Kevin Gifford contrasts ''Mechademia'' with shallower works on anime, praising its "insightful essays and reviews" and detail, calling it "worthwhile reading for anyone hungry for intelligent writing" about anime.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gifford |first=Kevin |title=Mechademia Volume 1 |magazine=Newtype USA |publisher=A.D. Vision |location=Houston, Texas, United States |volume=6 |issue=2 |page=139 |date=February 2007 |issn=1541-4817 }}</ref> Tomo Hirai of the ''Nichi Bei Times'' described the first volume as "an informative and inspiring read for those curious beyond the skin of ''anime''".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nichibeitimes.com/?p=1312 |title=Book Review: Academia and Fandom Meet In New Study of Anime and Manga |last=Hirai |first=Tomo |publisher=''Nichi Bei Times'' |accessdate=2009-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930012410/http://www.nichibeitimes.com/?p=1312 |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref><!--This dead link can not be retrieved/replaced by using Wayback Internet Archive-->
A review of the second volume of ''Mechademia'' by Comics Worth Reading's Johanna Draper Carlson criticises the journal for its dry tone and "flat statements following after each other separated only by footnote numbers".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicsworthreading.com/2008/09/14/mechademia-2-networks-of-desire/ |title=Mechademia 2: Networks of Desire |last=Draper Carlson |first=Johanna |date=September 14, 2008 |publisher=Comics Worth Reading |accessdate=2009-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125024629/http://comicsworthreading.com/2008/09/14/mechademia-2-networks-of-desire/ |archivedate=November 25, 2009 |df= }}</ref> A later review by Ed Sizemore recommends that ''Mechademia'' "should stop trying to develop a theme for each issue".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicsworthreading.com/2009/02/24/mechademia-3-limits-of-the-human/ |title=Mechademia 3: Limits of the Human |last=Sizemore |first=Ed |date=February 24, 2009 |publisher=Comics Worth Reading |accessdate=2009-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519052311/http://comicsworthreading.com/2009/02/24/mechademia-3-limits-of-the-human/ |archivedate=May 19, 2009 |df= }}</ref> Active Anime's Holly Ellingwood comments that the journal's "strong academic bent may put off some potential readers but give it a chance and peruse through the many varied topics".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://activeanime.com/html/2007/01/18/mechademia-emerging-worlds-of-anime-and-manga/ |title=Mechademia: Emerging Worlds of Anime and Manga |last=Ellingwood |first=Holly |date=January 18, 2007 |work=Active Anime |accessdate=2009-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228021836/http://activeanime.com/html/2007/01/18/mechademia-emerging-worlds-of-anime-and-manga/ |archivedate=December 28, 2011 |df= }} </ref> A later review by Scott Campbell commends the third volume of ''Mechademia'' as being "extremely insightful and thought provoking ... [about] anime, manga, and even the future of mankind".<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell |first=Scott |url=http://activeanime.com/html/2009/01/04/mechademia-vol-3-limits-of-the-human/ |title=Mechademia Vol 3: Limits of the Human |date=January 4, 2009 |work=Active Anime |accessdate=May 16, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228035631/http://activeanime.com/html/2009/01/04/mechademia-vol-3-limits-of-the-human/ |archivedate=December 28, 2011 |df= }} </ref> D. Harlan Wilson found the third volume to be "as accessible as it was provocative and enlightening".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wilson|first=D. Harlan|title=Lunning's Mechademia 3: Limits of the Human|url=http://www.depauw.edu/sfs/birs/bir111.html|journal=[[Science Fiction Studies]]|date=July 2010|authorlink=D. Harlan Wilson}}</ref>
William McClain criticises the fourth volume for having articles that are "too restrictive" in focus, calling attention to the lack of discussion, in this volume, of how anime and manga culture has spread internationally. McClain also criticises the volume for not including enough visual aids for the general reader, but praises the ''Mechademia'' journal as a whole for its experimental approach.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McClain |first=William |url=http://ijoc.org/ojs/index.php/ijoc/article/view/961/478 |title=Mechademia Volume 4: War/Time |work=International Journal of Communication |publisher= |volume=4 |year=2010 |accessdate=December 27, 2011 |format=PDF |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111231034636/http://ijoc.org/ojs/index.php/ijoc/article/view/961/478 |archivedate=December 31, 2011 |df= }} </ref> Ellen Grabiner feels that ''War/Time'' takes the approach that war has become a part of everyday life in post-war Japanese society, and praises the broad range of essays.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grabiner |first=Ellen |url=http://www.english.ufl.edu/imagetext/archives/v5_4/grabiner/ |title=Review of Mechademia 4: War/Time |work=ImageTexT: Interdisciplinary Comics Studies |publisher=University of Florida |volume=5 |issue=4 |year=2011 |accessdate=December 27, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228042017/http://www.english.ufl.edu/imagetext/archives/v5_4/grabiner/ |archivedate=December 28, 2011 |df= }} </ref> Timothy Iles feels that the strength of ''Mechademia'' is that it provides "theoretically informed, historically grounded, jargon-free research that highlights first and foremost, not the self-serving virtuosity of the researcher, but the interpretive depth of the material under analysis."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Iles |first=Timothy |url=http://www.japanesestudies.org.uk/reviews/2011/Iles3.html |title=Mechanical, Academic, Anime: Mechademia 4 and Mechademia 5 |work=Electronic Journal of Contemporary Japanese Studies |publisher= |date=May 31, 2011 |accessdate=December 27, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204042534/http://www.japanesestudies.org.uk/reviews/2011/Iles3.html |archivedate=February 4, 2012 |df= }} </ref>
